  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime and drug trafficking\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislation requiring financial institutions to report large transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970) - Expanded legal tools to combat organized crime\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n\n3. International Developments:\n- Vienna Convention (1988) - Established international framework for combating drug-related money laundering\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989 - Created global standards for anti-money laundering regulations\n\n4. Post-9/11 Expansion:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded money laundering regulations\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing prevention\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Progressively more comprehensive international agreements\n- Increased cooperation between countries in tracking and preventing money laundering\n\nThe legal landscape continues to evolve with technological changes and emerging financial practices.",
